{{About|the security consultant|the poet|León Félix Batista}} {{Infobox person | name = Felix Batista | image = | caption = | birth_name = Felix I. Batista | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Houston|Houston, Texas]] | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | disappeared_date = December 10, 2008 (aged 55) | disappeared_place = [[Mexico]] | disappeared_status = {{Missing for|2008|10|12}} | spouse = Lourdes Batista<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Felix|first=João Batista de Jesus|title="Hip Hop: cultura e política no contexto paulistano"|publisher=Universidade de Sao Paulo Sistema Integrado de Bibliotecas - SIBiUSP|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.11606/t.8.2006.tde-01052006-181824}}</ref> | children = 5 }} '''Felix Batista''' is a [[Cuban Americans|Cuban-American]]<ref name="eluniversal">{{cite news | last = Julieta | first = Martínez | title = Destaca México en número de secuestros | language = Spanish | publisher = [[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]] | date = 2008-02-21 | url = http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/vi_484282.html | accessdate = 2008-12-15}}</ref> anti-[[kidnapping]] expert and former [[U.S. Army]] [[major]] who has [[hostage negotiator|negotiated]] resolution to nearly 100 kidnapping and [[ransom]] cases,<ref name="yahoo">{{cite news|last=Stevenson |first=Mark |title=US anti-kidnapping expert kidnapped in Mexico |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |date=2008-12-15 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081215/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_mexico_american_kidnapped |accessdate=2008-12-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216021028/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081215/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_mexico_american_kidnapped |archivedate=December 16, 2008 }}</ref> dozens of them in [[Mexico]].<ref name="azcentral">{{cite news | title = Kidnappings soar in Mexico | publisher = AZ Central | date = 2008-04-23 | url = http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2008/04/23/20080423mexicokidnap23-on.html | accessdate = 2008-12-15}}</ref> Batista was a consultant for [[Houston|Houston, Texas]]-based security firm ASI Global.<ref name="yahoo"/> In December 2008, he was kidnapped in Mexico.
==Kidnapping== On December 10, 2008, Batista was kidnapped outside a restaurant in [[Saltillo|Saltillo, Coahuila, Mexico]] by unknown assailants<ref name="yahoo"/> while there to speak and give anti-kidnapping advice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lacey|first=Marc|title=Anti-kidnapping consultant kidnapped in Mexico|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/16/world/americas/16iht-16mexico.18709834.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 16, 2008}}</ref>
Batista was working as a negotiator to secure the release of a friend of his, while he was in a restaurant with several other people he received a phone call advising that the victim had been released and a car was being sent for him. As Batista left the restaurant he was forced into a Jeep by a group of four people who had been waiting for him. An hour later the kidnapping victim was released.<ref>{{cite web|title=Felix Batista|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/kidnap/felix-batista|website=[[FBI]]|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>
Since then, no one has had any communication with him and no one has ever claimed responsibility for his kidnapping {{as of|2016|June|lc=y}}.
A statement from Batista's family said there was no sign of violence at the scene.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/01/07/security.expert.kidnap/index.html | work=CNN | title='Please have mercy,' wife begs kidnappers - CNN.com | date=2009-01-07 | accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref>
==Military== Felix I. Batista, while a Major in the Florida Army National Guard and commander of a Military Intelligence Company was instrumental in developing a field training exercise called "Red Scorpion" which is now used NGB-wide by other National Guard Military Intelligence units.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}
